us rare earth policy needs short term focus by kia ghorashi lucinda gibbs polly hand and amber luong faculty advisor joe nation siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display us rare earth policy needs short term focus by kia ghorashi lucinda gibbs polly hand and amber luong faculty advisor joe nation type siepr policy brief author s kia ghorashi lucinda gibbs polly hand amber luong joe nation published 06 14 11 abstract china produces 97 percent of all rare earth elements rees consumed in the world today and it continues to restrict the export of these materials given that these materials are critical inputs to many important technologies should us policymakers be concerned yes and no on the positive side congress is now paying attention recently introducing the rare earth supply chain technology and resource transformation restart act of 2011 restart is still under committee consideration in the house and the united states has not yet adopted a specific and actionable ree policy that may be changing with the us department of energy doe december 2010 release of a critical materials strategy which quantifies potential ree supply disruptions and lays out a broad slate of general program and policy recommendations for the consideration of policymakers full text full text stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
